Day 3 — Package Types and Repository Configuration
Why Package Types Matter
Artifactory handles each package format differently:

Maven — understands pom.xml, handles snapshot/release logic
Docker — implements the Docker Registry HTTP API V2
npm — implements the npm registry protocol
PyPI — implements the PyPI simple index API
Helm — serves charts as a Helm repository
The package type determines which protocol Artifactory speaks with clients (Maven, Docker CLI, pip, npm, helm).

Maven Repositories
Maven has a concept of releases vs snapshots:

Release — stable, versioned artifacts (1.0.0, 2.3.1) — immutable once published
Snapshot — in-development versions (1.0.0-SNAPSHOT) — can be overwritten
Best practice: separate local repos for releases and snapshots.
libs-release-local    → only release artifacts
libs-snapshot-local   → only snapshot artifacts
Artifactory enforces this — you can configure a repo to accept only releases or only snapshots.

Docker Repositories
Artifactory acts as a fully compliant Docker registry. You:

docker login to Artifactory instead of Docker Hub
docker push images to your Artifactory repo
docker pull from Artifactory — either your own images (local) or proxied from Docker Hub (remote)
Each Docker local repo has a subdomain or path:

mycompany.jfrog.io/docker-local/myimage:1.0

PyPI Repositories
Artifactory acts as a PyPI index. Configure pip to use Artifactory:

pip install mypackage --index-url https://mycompany.jfrog.io/artifactory/api/pypi/pypi-virtual/simple

Helm Repositories
Store Helm charts for Kubernetes deployments. Artifactory serves as a Helm chart repository:

helm repo add myrepo https://mycompany.jfrog.io/artifactory/helm-virtual
helm install myapp myrepo/mychart

Generic Repositories
For anything that doesn't fit a specific package type — binaries, zip files, installers, scripts. Useful for storing build outputs that aren't standard packages.
